        {
            "@context":"https://schema.org",
            "@type":"FAQPage",
            "mainEntity":[{
                        "@type": "Question",
                        "name": "Is my money safe at First Tech Federal Credit Union?",
                        "acceptedAnswer": {
                            "@type": "Answer",
                            "text": "<p>First Tech protects its members\u2019 accounts and personal information by using the latest encryption technology and other modern security measures, like account authentication, alerts, fraud protection and more.<\/p>\n"
                        }
                    },{
                        "@type": "Question",
                        "name": "How do I join First Tech Federal Credit Union?",
                        "acceptedAnswer": {
                            "@type": "Answer",
                            "text": "<p>You can apply for membership to First Tech via the credit union\u2019s website or at any of its branch locations. You can become a member by meeting any of the criteria below:<\/p>\n<ul>\n<li>Work for one of the credit union\u2019s partner technology companies<\/li>\n<li>Work for the State of Oregon<\/li>\n<li>Work or live in Lane County, Oregon<\/li>\n<li>Be a family member of a First Tech member<\/li>\n<li>Be a member of the Computer History Museum<\/li>\n<li>Be a member of the Financial Fitness Association<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<p>You can gain membership to the Computer History Museum or Financial Fitness Association as part of the First Tech application process, but it requires paying a yearly membership fee.<\/p>\n"
                        }
                    },{
                        "@type": "Question",
                        "name": "What are share certificates? ",
                        "acceptedAnswer": {
                            "@type": "Answer",
                            "text": "<p>Share certificates are the credit union equivalent of certificates of deposit (CDs) commonly found at banks. Share certificate accounts hold a fixed amount of money for a fixed amount of time and typically earn higher interest rates than savings accounts. Like banks, credit unions may charge an early withdrawal fee if you withdraw funds from a share certificate account before its maturity date.<\/p>\n"
                        }
                    }]
        }

